er be a way to compare anyone directly to Tolkein.  It's just not apples to apples to try today.  Tolkein was in such a different time and environment it's not fair to even try to compare.  <br>
<br>
Martin's definitely written some of the most interesting, unpredictable stories I've ever read.  He does the literary equivalent of the rope-a-dope, showing one thing and then doing something completely different.  It's just so refreshing to read something where the &quot;good guy&quot; has a perfect plan to get him out of his current really bad situation, and the plan fails miserably.  At this point I couldn't even begin to guess what will happen with the next books.  And that's just the way it should be.  <br>
<br>
I have enjoyed Goodkind's Sword of Truth series, but I will agree it seemed to start high, and being to dip.  I was pretty disappointed with the last book I read (not sure if the next book had ever come out) that completely ignored the main characters of the previous books and focused on new ones.  It seemed to me one could introduce new characters without disregarding the ones you've spent a number of books developing.  Still, I do like Goodkind's writing style, Jordan became just plain tedious to me the last couple of books.  I think his latest one might be in hardcover?  No way in hell I'll touch it until it's paperback and on sale.  <br>
<br>
 <p>-Tain<BR>
